The paper discusses microarchitectural side-channel attacks and proposes a new attack called SPOILER that exploits the dependency resolution logic in modern microarchitectures. This makes the paper most likely to belong to the cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of SPOILER to improve cache attacks and Rowhammer attacks, which could also place it in the cs.AR (Architecture) and cs.SE (Software Engineering) sub-categories. The paper also discusses the use of speculative loads and store forwarding, which could place it in the cs.PL (Programming Languages) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the use of physical page mappings, which could place it in the cs.SY (Systems and Control) sub-category.
